comments: A very well put together route that connects many legal dirt roads. Most of the route lets you ride on legal dirt roads, open to traffic (yet there is almost none, since many portions of these roads are in pretty bad conditions). But the itinerary also includes some bits that are "Waldwege", which are forbidden to any motorized vehicles (unless you have a special authorization), so it's up to you to ride these particular roads. If you get caught the fine should be around 30 euros. You will ride through some remarkable scenery, especially in the M√§rkische Schweiz area. I rode the trail with a scrambler motorbike and didn't have any issues. The only difficulty you might encounter is when coming across some sandy spots, where the wheels will sink and loose grip/traction, but it's predominantly flat so not a big deal. Keep an eye out for other legal dirt roads that you will come across during this ride, and that you might want to go and explore (for instance when you get out of the woods just before Spitzm√ºhle, if you take a left hand turn you can ride to Wesendahl on some nice legal dirt roads). description text: Lovely little walk going through some beautiful countryside scenery, cutting through large fields full of windmills and greenery. We stopped at the Kinderbauernhof B√∂rnicke, a nice little farm, admiring all the animals, and made a longer break at the well known beer factory Erste Bernauer Braugenossenschaft e.G. - Brauerei Bernau. They make incredible craft beers and the ambient is great, since it's settled within a real, old, enormous factory. Afterwards, we made a circle through a forest back home. It was a beautiful day.

Another absolutely lovely walk around Bernau bei Berlin and neighboring villages, farms and parks. I can not get enough of these magical, endless fields spreading out as far as an eye can see. We saw a lot of horses, dozens of them, many cows, sheep and goats. We walked down the dirt roads, forest trails and some asphalt - but even then the road would go through some incredible forest or countryside. I feel I could walk through Bernau forever. It feels effortless, as it's all flat and all the trails are perfectly walkable. I was absolutely thrilled to find out that one of the Camino de Santiago trails is going through Bernau, basically in front of my building! I walked the Camino Frances a few years back, only a third of the road since I didn't have any more time, but I fell in love with it and I always plan on going back and doing the whole thing. Realizing a Camino is passing through my street was mind blowing! Now I wish to walk all the way from Northern Germany to Spain, haha!
